Black students aren’t graduating

on time because they are failing to.

live by the “four R’s” — righteous-
ness, representation, responsibility
and relationships.

This is according to Linwood
Harris, resident director of Lothrop
Hall and keynote speaker at the
Black Action Society’s 30th annual
Indaba celebration Friday night.

The Indaba is an informal dis-
cussion of issues affecting black
students’ academic success. A

Harris’ “four R’s” were among
the ideas presented to the nearly
450 people who attended the cele-
bration‘. ' A

“You aren’t righteous because
many of you walk around this cam-
pus without speaking to one anoth-

er,” Harris said.

Students tend to forget that they
represent their families based" on the
way that they act and carry them-
selves, he said.

“Your grandmother, mother and
ancestors are behind you,” Harris
said. “Is that they way you want to
portray them?”

Harris also said students think
that they are grown and don’t take
responsibility for their own lives.

“The relationships that you
establish while you’re in college
will help you to graduate,” Harris
said, “But first you must R.S.V.P.
[by following the four R’s].”

Friday’s celebration was
designed to help students avoid the
traps many black students run into
at Pitt. It was titled “Level 1” and
was meant to make the African—.
American community at Pitt better
than it was last year, said BAS pres-
ident Shavon Ogunleye. '

“In about two years, the people
who are at this podium won’t be
here,” said Ogunleye to students
during her opening speech. “And
we need someone to take our
places.” i

BAS needs to keep a stron
inﬂux of people and ideas in order
continue to serve Pitt’s black stu-
dents, Ogunleye said.

Harris advised students on how
to find their place in the.Pitt com-
munity without falling into the traps
that many African-Americans stu-
dents fall into.

“You’re in trouble with the sys-
tem you call higher education,” said
Harris.

Seventeen percent of black stu-
dents graduate from college, and 30
percent of those students graduate
in 5 to 6 years, according to Harris.

“This class [the class of ‘98] is
the best class in 24 years regarding

‘ where you rank in your class and

how well you did on the SATS, but
the statistics still aren’t changing,”
Harris said. “You’re still not gradu-
ating on time.”

Also, Justin Lang, of The
Village for an Afrikan Cultural
Center, spoke of his aspirations for
a cultural center so minority stu-
dents could have better access to
the Pitt community. ,

He said he hopes to build a rela-
tionship between the African-
American community and Pitt

through this cultural center. Lang
wants to establish study rooms and
libraries full of African history
books inside the center.

Darryl Wiley, president of My

Man Wear, told the students who
attended that he wanted to start an
entrepreneur club to teach members
how to run a successful business
with few mistakes.

