BATON ROUGE, La. (U-WlRE)—
Louisiana State University students experi-
encing problems with e-mail accounts and
Intemet access during the ﬁrst few weeks
of school may have computer hackers to
thank for it.

“We’re seeing all kind of hacker activ-
ity,” said Ronald Hay, executive director of
the Office of Computing Services.
“There’s a hell of a lot of nonsense going
on.”

During the ﬁrst two weeks of classes,
the University experienced problems with
Internet access and some e-mail accounts
due to hackers, Hay said ‘

“It’s not only om‘ site, but our Internet

‘ provider, Be1lSouth, has been having prob-

lems, too,” Hay said-.

Approximately 150 accounts were
compromised. The e-mail accounts that
experienced the problems were UNIXI
accounts, mostly held by graduate students
and faculty, said systems analyst Brian
Ropers-Huilman.

The hacked accounts belonged to stu-
dents who used easy-to-decipher pass-
words for logging in.

The initial intrusion-occurred at the
beginning of June. The hacker accessed
accounts allowing him to link to other
accounts, Ropers-Huilman said

“It took them to NASA, it took them to
Cornell, to IBM, Washington State,” he
said. And LSU was reﬂected as the place
where the intrusion was coming from.

“The repercussions of this person
intruding on our system [were] later in the
summer. We think this person took our
password ﬁle,” he said, “then apparently
posted the infonnation on the Internet
becausewehadarashofattacksinlate
summer, early fall.”

Some of the accounts intruded upon
had not been used frequently, Hay said

‘The. most attractive account is an
inactive account,” Hay said.

Although most of the intrusions were
not destructive, they were intrusive,
Ropers-Huilman said.

Hay attributes the increase in hacker

activity to the University’s rise in the

, national spotlight, due to the success of the

football and baseball teams.

When more people are taking notice of
a large group of computer users, that group
may become a target of hackers. -

“What we saw here this summer was a
rash of activity that was broader in scope
than we had ever seen,” Hay said.

The efforts to interrupt the
University’s services were the most persis-
tent during summer registration, he said.

‘They essentially brought our environ-
ment down,” Hay said.

An attack was used during registration
to overload the system,

Ropers-Huilman said.

“Somebody targeted us as well as the
University of Nebraska,” he said “Their
system went down, too. As far as I’m
aware, we have not had  [an] attack since
the fall semester has started.”_

When hacker activity is up, the
University increases its defenses, he said

The FBI was brought in to work with
the University on prosecuting some of the

- campus violations, Hay said.

“The FBI has formed a computer
crimes section in New Orleans for the ﬁrst
time,” Hay said.

Since June, the members of
Computing Services have met with the FBI
team to discuss legalities and prosecution.

“We were the ﬁrst university in the
Louisiana to meet with the computer
crimes division,” said Ropers-Huilman

Computing Services has been working
to ensure security for computer users since
these attacks.

“We’ve patched the security hole that
was exploited. Whenever we get a major
attack or when we get a lot of information
on small attacks, we turn this stuﬂ over to
the FBI,” he said.

ComputingServices has also installed
ﬁlters and other preventative measures,
Hay said, and have not experienced any
recent problems.

“We’re not having any serious prob-
lems as far as I know right now. We had a
whole rash of activity, but it’s calmed down
now,” Hay said. “Who knows, but tomor-
row’s a new day.”

